53: /**
54:  * Sink that emits its input elements to {@link FileSystem} files within buckets. This is integrated
55:  * with the checkpointing mechanism to provide exactly once semantics.
56:  *
57:  * <p>When creating the sink a {@code basePath} must be specified. The base directory contains one
58:  * directory for every bucket. The bucket directories themselves contain several part files, with at
59:  * least one for each parallel subtask of the sink which is writing data to that bucket. These part
60:  * files contain the actual output data.
61:  *
62:  * <p>The sink uses a {@link BucketAssigner} to determine in which bucket directory each element
63:  * should be written to inside the base directory. The {@code BucketAssigner} can, for example, use
64:  * time or a property of the element to determine the bucket directory. The default {@code
65:  * BucketAssigner} is a {@link DateTimeBucketAssigner} which will create one new bucket every hour.
66:  * You can specify a custom {@code BucketAssigner} using the {@code
67:  * setBucketAssigner(bucketAssigner)} method, after calling {@link
68:  * StreamingFileSink#forRowFormat(Path, Encoder)} or {@link StreamingFileSink#forBulkFormat(Path,
69:  * BulkWriter.Factory)}.
70:  *
71:  * <p>The names of the part files could be defined using {@link OutputFileConfig}. This
72:  * configuration contains a part prefix and a part suffix that will be used with the parallel
73:  * subtask index of the sink and a rolling counter to determine the file names. For example with a
74:  * prefix "prefix" and a suffix ".ext", a file named {@code "prefix-1-17.ext"} contains the data
75:  * from {@code subtask 1} of the sink and is the {@code 17th} bucket created by that subtask.
76:  *
77:  * <p>Part files roll based on the user-specified {@link RollingPolicy}. By default, a {@link
78:  * DefaultRollingPolicy} is used for row-encoded sink output; a {@link OnCheckpointRollingPolicy} is
79:  * used for bulk-encoded sink output.
80:  *
81:  * <p>In some scenarios, the open buckets are required to change based on time. In these cases, the
82:  * user can specify a {@code bucketCheckInterval} (by default 1m) and the sink will check
83:  * periodically and roll the part file if the specified rolling policy says so.
84:  *
85:  * <p>Part files can be in one of three states: {@code in-progress}, {@code pending} or {@code
86:  * finished}. The reason for this is how the sink works together with the checkpointing mechanism to
87:  * provide exactly-once semantics and fault-tolerance. The part file that is currently being written
88:  * to is {@code in-progress}. Once a part file is closed for writing it becomes {@code pending}.
89:  * When a checkpoint is successful the currently pending files will be moved to {@code finished}.
90:  *
91:  * <p>If case of a failure, and in order to guarantee exactly-once semantics, the sink should roll
92:  * back to the state it had when that last successful checkpoint occurred. To this end, when
93:  * restoring, the restored files in {@code pending} state are transferred into the {@code finished}
94:  * state while any {@code in-progress} files are rolled back, so that they do not contain data that
95:  * arrived after the checkpoint from which we restore.
96:  *
97:  * @param <IN> Type of the elements emitted by this sink
98:  * @deprecated Use {@link org.apache.flink.connector.file.sink.FileSink} instead.
99:  */
